ual life expectancy and sheer number of retirees, however, the current system faces an eventual overload. Alternative proposals have emerged, ranging from reductions in future benefits to a rise in taxrevenue to various forms of investment-based personal retirement accounts. As this volume suggests, the distributional consequences of these proposals are substantially different and may disproportionately affect those groups who depend on social security to avoid poverty in old age. Together, these studies persuasively show that appropriately designed investment-based social security reforms can effectively reduce the long-term burden of an aging society on future taxpayers, increase the expected future income of retirees, and mitigate poverty rates among the elderly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBusiness. 0aPension trusts. 0aPrivatization. 0aSocial sciences. 0aSocial security. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBrown, Jeffrey R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoronado, Julia Lynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeaton, Angus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeldstein, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeldstein, Martin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFullerton, Don, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlass, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGokhale, Jagadeesh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGourinchas, Pierre-Olivier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKotlikoff, Laurence J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiebman, Jeffrey B., econtributor